Pitch Check In \- Team 7

## Statement of Purpose

Conductor Tool makes managing software engineering courses way easier by automating the tedious stuff that takes up instructors' time. Right now, professors and TAs spend hours tracking who showed up to class, reading through scattered progress updates, and trying to figure out who's actually contributing to group projects. Our platform brings everything together in one place with user authentication, a class directory, attendance tracking, and daily work journals. This means teaching staff can quickly spot students who are struggling or falling behind, fairly evaluate everyone's contributions, and step in to help before small problems become big ones. By handling the administrative busywork automatically, Conductor Tool frees up instructors to actually teach and mentor students, while giving everyone clear visibility into participation and progress, making sure students stay accountable and get the support they need to succeed in team projects.

##  User Personas

**Alex Chen (The TA)**  
Alex Chen is a 23-year-old Master's student who works as a TA for Dr. Reed's course. As a "Group Mentor," he is the primary point of contact for 8-10 different student project teams, all while juggling his own research. His immediate thought is, "I have 10 teams. I just need a fast way to jot down who's doing what and who's falling behind, so I can grade fairly and know who to help during our check-ins."

Alex's main goal is to be an effective mentor, which requires him to recall the specific "particulars" of each team before his check-in meetings. He is highly motivated to grade all his students fairly based on their individual participation, not just the team's overall output. He wants to spend less time chasing students for status updates and more time helping them solve real engineering problems.

His biggest frustration is that his notes on teams are completely disorganized, scattered across random text files, Google Docs, and his own memory. He finds it extremely difficult to "assess each member’s involvement beyond the group’s overall progress" and feels he's only getting the perspective of the loudest person on each team. He wants to grade consistently but lacks a structured tool to track key participation metrics (like meeting attendance, task ownership, and conflicts) over the quarter.

Alex needs the Conductor Tool to provide a "Class Directory" view that is pre-filtered to show his assigned groups and their members. He needs a "very quick way to capture and recall meeting notes" that is simple and efficient. Most importantly, he needs a tool to track individual student metrics to justify his grades. This includes seeing his students' "Work Journal" entries and their attendance records for both lectures and team meetings.

**Dr. X (The Professor)**  
It's Sunday afternoon, and Dr. X is staring at her third spreadsheet. She's forming teams for 520 students—ten hours of manual work balancing skills, timezones, and schedules. This isn't why she became a professor.

X taught software architecture in industry for fifteen years before joining academia eight years ago. She loves watching students transform from coders into engineers, but managing 500+ students across fifty project teams means drowning in logistics instead of teaching. Every mid-quarter Wednesday, she cycles through Canvas, GitHub, Google Sheets, Slack, and email just to understand who's thriving and who's struggling. It takes ninety minutes to get a pulse on her class.

Last quarter, she almost missed Sarah Martinez in crisis. By the time Dr.X pieced together signals from five different tools—attendance dropping, commits slowing, journal entries stopping—it was week eight. Too close. How many other students slip through the cracks because information is scattered across systems that don't talk to each other?

Then there's the dependency nightmare. Three years ago, they built custom tools around Slack. The university switched to Teams. Everything broke. They lost months of development work. It happened again when vendors changed the grading system. Dr.X is cautious now—she needs abstractions and port-adaptor patterns that won't explode when services inevitably change. She also needs something simple enough that new TAs can learn it in an afternoon, maintainable enough that students can contribute without drowning in dependencies.

X knows exactly what would change her life. One place where she can see each student holistically—attendance, participation, code activity, journal entries, team dynamics. Early warnings that surface problems in week three, not week eight. Group formation that takes ninety minutes instead of ten hours. Flexibility to switch between GitHub and GitLab, Slack and Mattermost, without rebuilding everything.  
Most importantly, sustainability. Simple architecture, minimal dependencies, vanilla technologies. Documentation clear enough for anyone to jump in. She wants Conductor to work five years from now, not become another abandoned project.

"Every student deserves to be seen, even in a class of 500," she says. "Technology should help with that, not make it harder."

**Marcus (The Team Lead)**  
Marcus checks his phone between classes—three unread messages in the team Slack, two GitHub notifications, and a reminder about tomorrow's standup. He's the team leader for his CSE 110 group, and honestly, he's drowning. He signed up for this role thinking it would look good on his resume, but now he spends more time chasing people down than actually building software.

It's Tuesday night, and Marcus needs to figure out who can meet Thursday for sprint planning. He opens a shared Google Doc where people are supposed to update their availability, but it's two weeks out of date. He pings the Slack channel. Three people respond immediately, two don't see it until midnight, and one doesn't respond at all. By the time he's coordinated everyone, it's 11pm and he hasn't written a line of code. Meanwhile, he knows two team members are quietly doing all the work while others coast, but he has no concrete way to document this for the TA.

Last week during their meeting, he noticed Alex seemed stressed and distracted. Marcus wanted to flag this to their TA early—maybe Alex needs help or is overloaded—but there's no formal channel. Should he send an email? Drop by office hours? Write it in some random Google Doc? By the time he figured out the process, two more weeks passed and Alex had fallen further behind.

Marcus needs one place to run his team. A dashboard showing everyone's availability, their recent contributions, and their sentiment from standup journals. He needs to track attendance without maintaining another spreadsheet. He needs private notes about team dynamics that feed directly to the TA without awkward conversations. He wants to see who's carrying the team and who's struggling—not to punish anyone, but to lead effectively and get help before small problems become crises.

Most importantly, Marcus wants to spend his time being a leader and building software, not playing administrative coordinator across six different tools. He volunteered for leadership to learn and grow, not to manage spreadsheets.

"I just want to lead my team, not chase them down," he says.

**Aisha Patel (The Student)**  
Aisha sits in the back of the lecture hall, laptop open but hands still. She has thoughts about the architecture decision being discussed—she spent three hours last night refactoring their API layer—but ten hands are already up and the conversation is moving fast. By the time there's space to speak, the moment has passed. Again. Does anyone even know she's contributing?

It's week seven, and Aisha is exhausted. She's committed over forty times to the repository, written most of the backend, and debugged critical issues at midnight. But in meetings, she's quiet. She listens, processes, then codes. Meanwhile, three teammates who talk constantly but commit rarely seem more visible. When grades come, will the TA know what she actually did? Will her team leader remember that she rebuilt the entire database schema? Or will she be marked down for "lack of participation" because she doesn't perform enthusiasm in meetings?

Last week, Aisha's grandmother fell ill. She needed to miss two meetings and reduce her workload temporarily. She mentioned it in Slack, but the message got buried. By Thursday, her team leader was frustrated about missed deadlines, and Aisha felt guilty and overwhelmed. She needed a clear way to communicate her status—not dramatically, just factually—so the team could adjust expectations and she wouldn't be silently drowning.

Aisha also has concerns about team dynamics. One member keeps dismissing her suggestions, and another hasn't touched the codebase in three weeks. She wants to document this privately—not to be vindictive, but to protect herself and provide honest feedback that might help future teams. But there's nowhere safe to do this. Email feels too formal. Slack isn't private. Speaking up in meetings risks confrontation.

What Aisha needs is simple: recognition for her actual contributions, a way to communicate her status clearly, and a private channel for honest feedback. She wants transparent evaluation criteria so she knows if she's on track. She wants to be seen—not just heard.

## Feature 1: Authentication/User Management

### **Problem:**

Authentication: The conductor tool needs to be able to authenticate users as associated with UCSD. For those who don’t exist in the database, they need to sign up. This also includes UCSD extension students who don’t have a UCSD email, and they need to contact the administrator to sign up.

User Management: The conductor tool needs to be able to configure access for each user role. If there are people who decide to drop or accidentally join the class, there needs to be a way to remove them from the class. The instructor and TAs need to have the ability to automatically assign Team Leaders and Groups to the students so they can begin work as early and efficiently as possible. They also need to be able to reassign Team Leaders and Groups if the initial assignment is not satisfactory.

###  **Appetite:**

Authentication: This will be done within the first sprint, as it serves as the entry-point for the web-app and needs to be set up first. By doing authentication first, we have established a form of security within our system.

User Management: We plan to get this done by the end of sprint two. This should enable users (like admin, professor, TA) to manage other users (tutor, students, TL). 

###  **Solution:**

Authentication  
Authentication typically uses UCSD email to verify that the user is associated with UCSD. Users who do not have a UCSD email, like extension students, can send a request form to the system administrator. The system administrator can verify if the user is allowed to take this class and manually add them to the database. In addition to being verified as associated with UCSD, students must also provide a verification code that can only be found if they are enrolled in the class (Canvas, Class Slack, etc.). This code will automatically assign them the student role. Every role will have a different verification code that is configured by the system administrator. 

Sign Up/In For UCSD Students:  
Provide UCSD email, First and Last Name, ~~and create a password~~. Signing in requires the UCSD email (Google authentication) and associated password. Afterwards, they need to provide their verification code.

Sign Up/In for Extension Students:  
Request Form: Provide their school-associated email, First and Last Name. Afterwards, they need to provide their verification code to send the request form. Then, they can use Google authentication to log in if they are approved by the system administrator.

User Management  
We first establish our hierarchy of user roles as shown below:

1. System Administrator (Like root)  
2. Instructor (root privileges)  
3. Teaching Assistant  
4. Tutor  
5. Student Leader  
6. Student

The System Administrator, Instructor, and Teaching Assistant have the ability to configure roles that are below themselves in the hierarchy (this includes deleting the user). Each user profile will have these associated attributes when stored in the database, which allows us to figure out what role they have and what can be read (for Class Directory). As for specific capabilities (such as what they can see), we will need to have a better understanding of the other features.

###  **Rabbit Holes:**

Authentication: Potential issues using verification code-based authentication would be that they can be shared. We assume Instructors/TAs/Tutors are responsible enough not to leak their codes. Students, however, are more likely to share their code with non-students, populating the class with excess profiles. As of now, we will assume that not many people are interested in signing up for a class they are not related to, so that Instructors/TAs/Tutors/SysAdmin can manually delete any profiles that do not seem to match with the registration list (provided by WebReg, Canvas, etc).

User management: On the topic of system administration, the consequences are unclear whether having multiple administrators or being able to transfer the power of a system administrator poses security risks. We also think the system administrators are solely responsible for managing the user roles and authentication; they are not a superset of the capabilities of the instructors/TAs.

###  **No-goes:**

Authentication: We will not use UCSD SSO for authentication purposes because that might involve working with ITS on sensitive data and causing unnecessary trouble. We will not handle account recovery flows beyond basic admin resets (e.g., no password reset emails or SSO recovery). We will not provide full audit logging or activity tracking for user management actions beyond simple database records.

User management: We will not support cross-course synchronization with systems like Canvas, Gradescope, or WebReg — any updates to user rosters will be done manually by admins or instructors. We will not build advanced permission inheritance or custom role creation; roles will be fixed (System Administrator, Instructor, TA, Tutor, Team Leader, Student). We will not allow users to self-assign or modify their own roles — only higher-level roles can assign or change them.

## Feature 2: Class Directory

### **Problem**

Teaching staff (Professors, TAs) and students (especially Team Leaders) need a centralized, reliable, and easy-to-navigate location to see who is in the course, what their role is, and how they are grouped. Currently, this information is often scattered across different, disconnected systems like a basic Canvas roster, Slack profiles, or separate spreadsheets.

This makes it difficult to:

* Quickly find contact information or office hours.  
* Understand the-structure of the class (who are the TAs, Tutors, etc.).  
* See which students are on which teams.  
* Provide a central "hub" for a user to see their own status and links relevant to them.

The Class Directory feature must solve this by reading from the user database (managed by the User Management feature) and presenting this information in a structured, role-appropriate, and domain-specific way.

### **Appetite**

This is a core MVP feature and is the primary "read" component for the "User Management" feature. It's essential for providing context to all other features (like Attendance and Work Journals).

Our subteam plans to deliver the core functionality for this feature by the **end of Sprint 3**.

* **Sprint 2:** Focus on the database schema (in collaboration with the Auth team) and building the static pages/components for the Roster and Profile pages.  
* **Sprint 3:** Connect these pages to the live database and API endpoints, implement filtering/search, and refine the role-based permissions for what data is displayed.

### **Solution**

Our subteam will implement this feature by creating four primary page/view types, which will serve as the main user interface for the application:

* **User Dashboard Page:** This will be the personalized landing page for a logged-in user. It will act as a central navigation hub, providing quick links to their own profile, their group's page (if they are in a group), and the main Class Roster.  
* **Class Roster Page:** This will be the main directory, displaying a searchable and filterable list of all users in the course (Professors, TAs, Tutors, and Students). Key features include:  
  * Search by name.  
  * Filter by role (e.g., "Show only TAs").  
  * Filter by group (e.g., "Show only Team 7").  
  * Each entry will be a summary "card" with a name, photo, and role, which clicks through to their full profile.  
* **User Profile Page:** This is the detailed view for a single individual. The information displayed will be **dynamic** based on the user's role and the *viewer's* permissions.  
  * **All profiles** will show basic info: Name, Pronunciation, Pronouns, Photo, and Role.  
  * **Student profiles** will also show their Group, Contact Info, Availability, and placeholders for their Activity/Attendance/Journal links.  
  * **Staff (Prof/TA/Tutor) profiles** will prominently display their Contact Information, Availability (office hours), and (for TAs) a list of the groups they are responsible for.  
* **Group Information Page:** This will be a dedicated page for each project team. It will display:  
  * Group Name, Logo, and Mantra.  
  * A list of all group members (with links to their User Profile pages).  
  * Links to the group's external resources (Repo, Slack/chat, etc.).  
  * Placeholders for group-level announcements, calendar/availability, and shared issues.

This feature is the "read" interface for the user data. We will work closely with the Authentication/User Management team to define the necessary database schema and API endpoints to populate these pages.

### **Rabbit Holes**

* **Permission Complexity:** The biggest risk is managing *who* can see *what*. For example, a student viewing another student's profile should see less information (e.g., no detailed attendance record) than a TA viewing that same student's profile. We must clearly define these view-level permissions with the Auth team to comply with FERPA and avoid data leaks.  
* **Data Integration Creep:** The profile and group pages are meant to link to *other features* (Attendance, Work Journal, Repo activity). A rabbit hole would be trying to *build* those data-collection features ourselves. **Our Scope:** Our team will only build the UI components to *display* this information. We will define clear API contracts and build placeholders, assuming other teams will provide the data endpoints.  
* **Profile Editing:** It's unclear where "viewing" a profile (our feature) ends and "editing" a profile (User Management feature) begins. We will assume our team is **read-only**. We will work with the User Management team to ensure they provide a clear "Edit Profile" flow that our pages can link to.  
* **Performance:** Loading a roster page with 500+ students (including photos and details) could be very slow. We must implement **pagination** and efficient database queries from the beginning to ensure the Roster Page is fast and usable.

## Feature 3: Attendance System

### 

### **Problem**

No centralized, reliable way to record attendance across different meeting types (lectures, office hours, team meetings, etc.).  
Manual attendance tracking is time-consuming and error-prone.  
Students cannot easily verify their attendance or confirm if they’ve been marked correctly.  
Lack of visibility into attendance trends or history over time.

### **Appetite**

Our team aims to deliver the core attendance functionality by **the end of Sprint 3**, focusing first on accuracy and reliability before adding advanced features.

**Sprint 1**

* Implement **meeting creation and management system**.  
* Enable instructors to **record and update attendance manually**.

**Sprint 2**

* Add **automatic/student-side attendance recording** using QR or alphanumeric code.  
* Build a **calendar view** for upcoming and past meetings/attendance.

**Sprint 3**

* Implement **attendance insights and analytics** over time.

### **Solution**

The attendance system is built around a **centralized relational database** that stores all meeting, user, and attendance information. Each functional module interacts with this database to ensure consistent, real-time, and reliable data flow.

#### **Meeting Management**

* Use the database to store and manage meeting records, including:  
  * Meeting type (Lecture, Office Hour, Team Meeting, etc.)  
  * Time, location, and meeting description  
  * Expected attendees  
* When a new meeting is created, expected members are automatically linked in the database to generate attendance records.

#### **Attendance Recording**

* **Manual mode:** Instructors can record, update, and correct attendance directly through the interface, which updates the database.

* **Automatic mode:** Students check in using **QR codes or temporary alphanumeric codes**, which write verified attendance entries into the database.

* Optimized for **fast recording (\<1 minute)** and scalable to **200+ users** simultaneously.

#### **User Interface (UI/UX)**

* **Student View:**  
  * Displays attendance records and history.  
  * Calendar view showing upcoming and past meetings.  
  * Check-in page: Allows students to join an active meeting and mark their attendance (e.g., via code, QR, or one-click).  
  * Real-time feedback (e.g., “Attendance marked successfully” or “Session closed”).  
* **Instructor View:**  
  * Dashboard displaying meeting summaries, participant lists, and attendance status, with edit capability.  
  * Visualize data trends (e.g., attendance rate by week, meeting type, or student).  
  * Calendar view of all scheduled meetings.  
  * Start Attendance session: Option to initiate a new check-in session for a specific meeting, view who has joined, and close it when done.

### **Rabbit Holes**

Handling **large-scale simultaneous check-ins** (200+ users) without delay or data loss.  
Preventing **false or proxy attendance** (verifying real physical presence).  
Designing a **simple, intuitive UI** for both quick check-in and correction.  
Ensuring **data integrity** if the app crashes mid-recording.  
Check **device compatibility** for QR check-in.

**No Goes**

* **Offline/ Network-Failure Support:** Network issues or server downtime could prevent successful check-ins. We will assume that nominal use of the app depends on stable network connectivity and will not provide offline support.  
* **Biometric or geolocation attendance tracking;** Features like facial recognition, GPS-based verification, or Bluetooth proximity are explicitly excluded due to privacy and technical complexity.  
* **Advanced analytics or AI-based trend prediction:** Analytics are limited to visual summaries and basic trend charts (e.g., attendance rate over time).

## Feature 4: Work-Journal/ Standup Tool

### **Problem**

**Students forget what they’ve accomplished and struggle to communicate progress effectively.**

In project-based courses with 4–5 person teams, students juggle multiple classes and lose track of their daily contributions. When TAs ask *“what did you work on this week?”*, students draw blanks or undersell their work. Meanwhile, TAs managing 15–25 students across multiple teams can’t identify struggling students until it’s too late—often after they’ve fallen weeks behind.

**Current solutions (Slack messages, email updates, synchronous standups) have critical flaws:**

* **Async text updates:** Get buried in channels, no historical view, hard to track participation

* **Synchronous meetings:** Impossible to schedule with students in 3–5 different courses

* **Generic tools (Jira, Trello):** Too heavyweight, require manual entry, no academic context

* **Nothing at all:** TAs rely on sporadic check-ins, missing early warning signs

**The gap:** No lightweight tool that captures daily work, surfaces blockers automatically, and gives TAs early warning about at-risk students—all in under 2 minutes per day.

**Real pain points**

* Students can’t articulate what they’ve done when grading time comes

* Blockers go unreported for days because *“I didn’t want to bother the TA”*

* TAs discover inactivity only at final demos

* Participation grading is subjective and unfair without data

* GitHub commits don’t tell the full story (research, debugging, helping teammates)

### **Appetite**

**2 weeks for MVP (one development cycle)**

This is a small-batch project with clear boundaries.

We’re *not* building a full project-management system—just a focused daily check-in tool that integrates with existing workflows (GitHub, Slack/Discord).

**Scope limits**

* Web-first (mobile responsive, no native apps)

* GitHub integration only (skip Jira, GitLab)

* Slack/Emailnotifications only (no Discord)

* Manual team setup (no LMS integration in MVP)

* Basic sentiment tracking (advanced analytics post-MVP)

**Success criteria**

* Students can submit daily check-ins in \<2 minutes

* TAs see aggregated team health at a glance

* Blocker alerts escalate automatically after 4 hours

* System handles 200 students across 40 teams without performance issues

### **Solution**

**A three-tier daily check-in system with automatic GitHub integration and intelligent escalation**

#### Core Loop (Student View)

The student view auto-populates GitHub activity from the last 24 hours. One-click inclusion reduces manual entry. The three-question format (Yesterday/Today/Blockers) takes under 2 minutes to complete. Sentiment emojis remain grayscale until selected, minimizing visual noise.

**Daily 2-minute check-in with smart defaults**

Students answer three questions:

1. **What did you accomplish yesterday?**

   * Auto-populated with GitHub activity (commits, PRs, reviews from last 24 hours)

   * One-click to include: “✓ Include 3 commits to feature/auth”

   * Manual additions for non-code work (research, design, meetings)

2. **What will you work on today?**

   * Pre-filled with yesterday’s “today” plan

   * Students edit/update as needed

3. **Any blockers?**

   * Empty by default

   * When filled → triggers team notification

   * Optional: tag teammates (“@sarah for auth advice”)

#### **![][image2]**

#### Team Dashboard (Collaborative View)

Team members view each other's check-ins in real-time. Blocker alerts are highlighted with action buttons for peer help or TA escalation.  
The 7-day sentiment trend chart shows team morale over time. Missing submissions are tracked with gentle nudges, not punitive alerts.

**Example flow**

1. Alex reports “database connection pooling timeout”

2. Sarah clicks *I can help* → both notified

3. If unresolved \> 4 hrs → TA auto-notified

4. Alex marks resolved → logs peer support credit

Priority alerts surface urgent issues first (active blockers, missing students, sentiment drops). The team overview table provides at-a-glance health metrics with trend indicators (↑↓→). At-risk students are auto-detected using a point-based scoring system. TAs can drill down into individual teams with one click.

### **Rabbit Holes**

3rd Party app integration: In the feature of connecting to TA’s, Professors there are a lot of methods and apps to use for it. We might get sucked into trying to overoptimise it and try to integrate apps that are too complicated. As of now we are planning to do a slack integration that can be plugged in and out based on availability.

Bot: We are also planning to add bots for Standup reminders, git push notifications, meeting notifications etc. If we are not careful then we might end up try to add a lot of features, some that are not very useful but hard to implement.

**No Goes**

Sentiment Analysis: There was a suggestion among the group to use Amazon's sentiment analysis for the TA’s to understand the class and teams mood/enthusiasm, but this would be very complicated and unnecessary, hence we want a simple mood option with each standup (0-5 stars), for a simple sentiment analysis.
